(and may over-flag legitimate campaigns that naturally produce high repetition. The) Tj
T*
(thresholds should be recalibrated when traffic mix, geography, or ad inventory changes) Tj
T*
(materially.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
( 5. Probability assessment) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The estimated probability that a flagged event is fraudulent is 69%. This is not label-) Tj
T*
(calibrated precision; it is a reasoned estimate based on agreement between independent) Tj
T*
(signals. Events flagged by both the heuristic model and the upper tail of the ML anomaly) Tj
T*
(score are more likely to be fraudulent than events flagged by only one weak signal. The) Tj
T*
(report therefore treats probability as an operational confidence estimate, not a) Tj
T*
(measured ground truth metric.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
( 6. Recommended actions) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Assuming false positives and false negatives are roughly equal in cost, the submitted) Tj
T*
(binary prediction uses the combined score threshold rather than only the highest-) Tj
T*
(confidence intersection. For business action, use three tiers: suppress the highest) Tj
T*
(combined-score traffic, quarantine medium-confidence traffic for review, and monitor) Tj
T*
(low-confidence anomalies until labels are available.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
( 7. Future work) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(With more time, I would add labeled validation data, campaign-level normalization,) Tj
T*
(browser/user-agent fingerprinting if available, time-series burst detection by) Tj
T*
(inventory, calibrated probabilities, and a feedback loop from manual review decisions.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
